# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-batch
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] In computing, **batch processing** is the running of a software job in an automated and unattended way.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] A user schedules a job to run and then waits for a processing system to run it.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Typically, a job is scheduled to run at a configured time of day or when an event occurs or when computer resources are available.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] The term "batch processing" originates in the traditional classification of methods of production as job production (one-off production), batch production (production of a "batch" of multiple items at once, one stage at a time), and flow production (mass production, all stages in process at once).
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Early computers were capable of running only one program at a time.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Each user had sole control of the machine for a scheduled period of time.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] They would arrive at the computer with program and data, often on punched paper cards and magnetic or paper tape, and would load their program, run and debug it, and carry off their output when done.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] As computers became faster the setup and takedown time became a larger percentage of available computer time.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Programs called *monitors*, the forerunners of operating systems, were developed which could process a series, or "batch", of programs, often from magnetic tape prepared offline.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] The monitor would be loaded into the computer and run the first job of the batch.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] At the end of the job it would regain control and load and run the next until the batch was complete.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Often the output of the batch would be written to magnetic tape and printed or punched offline.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Examples of monitors were IBM's *Fortran Monitor System*, SOS (Share Operating System), and finally IBSYS for IBM's 709x systems in 1960.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Third-generation computers capable of multiprogramming began to appear in the 1960s.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Instead of running one batch job at a time, these systems can have multiple batch programs running at the same time in order to keep the system as busy as possible.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] One or more programs might be awaiting input, one actively running on the CPU, and others generating output.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Instead of offline input and output, programs called spoolers read jobs from cards, disk, or remote terminals and place them in a job queue to be run.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] In order to prevent deadlocks the job scheduler needs to know each job's resource requirements—memory, magnetic tapes, mountable disks, etc., so various scripting languages were developed to supply this information in a structured way.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Probably the most well-known is IBM's *Job Control Language* (JCL).
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Job schedulers select jobs to run according to a variety of criteria, including priority, memory size, etc.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Remote batch is a procedure for submitting batch jobs from remote terminals, often equipped with a punch card reader and a line printer.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Sometimes asymmetric multiprocessing is used to spool batch input and output for one or more large computers using an attached smaller and less-expensive system, as in the IBM System/360 Attached Support Processor.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] The first general-purpose time-sharing system, Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), was compatible with batch processing.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] This facilitated transitioning from batch processing to interactive computing.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] From the late 1960s onwards, interactive computing such as via text-based computer terminal interfaces (as in Unix shells or read-eval-print loops), and later graphical user interfaces became common.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation, both one-off jobs such as compilation, and processing of multiple items in batches, became retrospectively referred to as *batch processing*, and the term *batch job* (in early use often "batch *of* jobs") became common.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Early use is particularly found at the University of Michigan, around the Michigan Terminal System (MTS).
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Although timesharing did exist, its use was not robust enough for corporate data processing; none of this was related to the earlier unit record equipment, which was human-operated.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation remains widespread in computing, both for general data processing and for system "housekeeping" tasks (using system software).
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] A high-level program (executing multiple programs, with some additional "glue" logic) is today most often called a *script*, and written in scripting languages, particularly shell scripts for system tasks; in IBM PC DOS and MS-DOS this is instead known as a batch file.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] That includes UNIX-based computers, Microsoft Windows, macOS (whose foundation is the BSD Unix kernel), and even smartphones.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] A running script, particularly one executed from an interactive login session, is often known as a job, but that term is used very ambiguously.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] "There is no direct counterpart to z/OS batch processing in PC or UNIX systems.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Batch jobs are typically executed at a scheduled time or on an as-needed basis.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Batch applications are still critical in most organizations in large part because many common business processes are amenable to batch processing.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] While online systems can also function when manual intervention is not desired, they are not typically optimized to perform high-volume, repetitive tasks.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Therefore, even new systems usually contain one or more batch applications for updating information at the end of the day, generating reports, printing documents, and other non-interactive tasks that must complete reliably within certain business deadlines.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Some applications are amenable to flow processing, namely those that only need data from a single input at once (not totals, for instance): start the next step for each input as it completes the previous step.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] In this case flow processing lowers latency for individual inputs, allowing them to be completed without waiting for the entire batch to finish.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] However, many applications require data from all records, notably computations such as totals.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] In this case the entire batch must be completed before one has a usable result: partial results are not usable.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Modern batch applications make use of modern batch frameworks such as Jem The Bee, Spring Batch or implementations of JSR 352 written for Java, and other frameworks for other programming languages, to provide the fault tolerance and scalability required for high-volume processing.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] In order to ensure high-speed processing, batch applications are often integrated with grid computing solutions to partition a batch job over a large number of processors, although there are significant programming challenges in doing so.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] High volume batch processing places particularly heavy demands on system and application architectures as well.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Architectures that feature strong input/output performance and vertical scalability, including modern mainframe computers, tend to provide better batch performance than alternatives.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Scripting languages became popular as they evolved along with batch processing.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] A *batch window* is "a period of less-intensive online activity", when the computer system is able to run batch jobs without interference from, or with, interactive online systems.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] A bank's *end-of-day (EOD)* jobs require the concept of *cutover*, where transaction and data are cut off for a particular day's batch activity ("deposits after 3 PM will be processed the next day").
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] As requirements for online systems uptime expanded to support globalization, the Internet, and other business needs, the batch window shrank and increasing emphasis was placed on techniques that would require online data to be available for a maximum amount of time.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] The *batch size* refers to the number of work units to be processed within one batch operation.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] The IBM mainframe z/OS operating system or platform has arguably the most highly refined and evolved set of batch processing facilities owing to its origins, long history, and continuing evolution.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Today such systems commonly support hundreds or even thousands of concurrent online and batch tasks within a single operating system image.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] The Unix programs `cron`, `at`, and `batch` (today `batch` is a variant of `at`) allow for complex scheduling of jobs.
[src:aws-batch/batch-processing] Most high-performance computing clusters use batch processing to maximize cluster usage.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Grids are a form of distributed computing composed of many networked loosely coupled computers acting together to perform large tasks.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] This is in contrast to the traditional notion of a supercomputer, which has many processors connected by a local high-speed computer bus.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Grid computing combines computers from multiple administrative domains to reach a common goal, to solve a single task, and may then disappear just as quickly.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The size of a grid may vary from small—confined to a network of computer workstations within a corporation, for example—to large, public collaborations across many companies and networks.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] "The notion of a confined grid may also be known as an intra-nodes cooperation whereas the notion of a larger, wider grid may thus refer to an inter-nodes cooperation".
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Coordinating applications on grids can be a complex task, especially when coordinating the flow of information across distributed computing resources.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Grid workflow systems have been developed as a specialized form of a workflow management system designed specifically to compose and execute a series of computational or data manipulation steps, or a workflow, in the grid context.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The primary performance disadvantage is that the various processors and local storage areas do not have high-speed connections.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] This arrangement is thus well-suited to applications in which multiple parallel computations can take place independently, without the need to communicate intermediate results between processors.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The high-end scalability of geographically dispersed grids is generally favorable, due to the low need for connectivity between nodes relative to the capacity of the public Internet.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] There are also some differences between programming for a supercomputer and programming for a grid computing system.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] It can be costly and difficult to write programs that can run in the environment of a supercomputer, which may have a custom operating system, or require the program to address concurrency issues.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] If a problem can be adequately parallelized, a “thin” layer of “grid” infrastructure can allow conventional, standalone programs, given a different part of the same problem, to run on multiple machines.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] This makes it possible to write and debug on a single conventional machine and eliminates complications due to multiple instances of the same program running in the same shared memory and storage space at the same time.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] One feature of distributed grids is that they can be formed from computing resources belonging to one or multiple individuals or organizations (known as multiple administrative domains).
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] This can facilitate commercial transactions, as in utility computing, or make it easier to assemble volunteer computing networks.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] One disadvantage of this feature is that the computers which are actually performing the calculations might not be entirely trustworthy.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The designers of the system must thus introduce measures to prevent malfunctions or malicious participants from producing false, misleading, or erroneous results, and from using the system as an attack vector.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] This often involves assigning work randomly to different nodes (presumably with different owners) and checking that at least two different nodes report the same answer for a given work unit.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Discrepancies would identify malfunctioning and malicious nodes.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] However, due to the lack of central control over the hardware, there is no way to guarantee that nodes will not drop out of the network at random times.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Some nodes (like laptops or dial-up Internet customers) may also be available for computation but not network communications for unpredictable periods.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] These variations can be accommodated by assigning large work units (thus reducing the need for continuous network connectivity) and reassigning work units when a given node fails to report its results in the expected time.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The impacts of trust and availability on performance and development difficulty can influence the choice of whether to deploy onto a dedicated cluster, to idle machines internal to the developing organization, or to an open external network of volunteers or contractors.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] In many cases, the participating nodes must trust the central system not to abuse the access that is being granted, by interfering with the operation of other programs, mangling stored information, transmitting private data, or creating new security holes.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Other systems employ measures to reduce the amount of trust “client” nodes must place in the central system such as placing applications in virtual machines.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Public systems or those crossing administrative domains (including different departments in the same organization) often result in the need to run on heterogeneous systems, using different operating systems and hardware architectures.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] With many languages, there is a trade-off between investment in software development and the number of platforms that can be supported (and thus the size of the resulting network).
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Cross-platform languages can reduce the need to make this tradeoff, though potentially at the expense of high performance on any given node (due to run-time interpretation or lack of optimization for the particular platform).
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Various middleware projects have created generic infrastructure to allow diverse scientific and commercial projects to harness a particular associated grid or for the purpose of setting up new grids.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] BOINC is a common one for various academic projects seeking public volunteers; more are listed at the end of the article.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] In fact, the middleware can be seen as a layer between the hardware and the software.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] On top of the middleware, a number of technical areas have to be considered, and these may or may not be middleware independent.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Example areas include SLA management, Trust, and Security, Virtual organization management, License Management, Portals and Data Management.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] These technical areas may be taken care of in a commercial solution, though the cutting edge of each area is often found within specific research projects examining the field.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The overall grid market comprises several specific markets.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] These are the grid middleware market, the market for grid-enabled applications, the utility computing market, and the software-as-a-service (SaaS) market.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Grid middleware is a specific software product, which enables the sharing of heterogeneous resources, and Virtual Organizations.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] It is installed and integrated into the existing infrastructure of the involved company or companies and provides a special layer placed among the heterogeneous infrastructure and the specific user applications.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Major grid middlewares are Globus Toolkit, gLite, and UNICORE.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Utility computing is referred to as the provision of grid computing and applications as service either as an open grid utility or as a hosting solution for one organization or a VO.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Major players in the utility computing market are Sun Microsystems, IBM, and HP.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Grid-enabled applications are specific software applications that can utilize grid infrastructure.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] This is made possible by the use of grid middleware, as pointed out above.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Software as a service (SaaS) is “software that is owned, delivered and managed remotely by one or more providers.” (Gartner 2007) Additionally, SaaS applications are based on a single set of common code and data definitions.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] They are consumed in a one-to-many model, and SaaS uses a Pay As You Go (PAYG) model or a subscription model that is based on usage.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Providers of SaaS do not necessarily own the computing resources themselves, which are required to run their SaaS.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Therefore, SaaS providers may draw upon the utility computing market.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The utility computing market provides computing resources for SaaS providers.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] For companies on the demand or user side of the grid computing market, the different segments have significant implications for their IT deployment strategy.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The IT deployment strategy as well as the type of IT investments made are relevant aspects for potential grid users and play an important role for grid adoption.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Many volunteer computing projects, such as BOINC, use the CPU scavenging model.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Since nodes are likely to go "offline" from time to time, as their owners use their resources for their primary purpose, this model must be designed to handle such contingencies.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Creating an **Opportunistic Environment** is another implementation of CPU-scavenging where special workload management system harvests the idle desktop computers for compute-intensive jobs, it also refers as Enterprise Desktop Grid (EDG).
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Like other full-featured batch systems, HTCondor provides a job queueing mechanism, scheduling policy, priority scheme, resource monitoring, and resource management.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] It can be used to manage workload on a dedicated cluster of computers as well or it can seamlessly integrate both dedicated resources (rack-mounted clusters) and non-dedicated desktop machines (cycle scavenging) into one computing environment.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The term *grid computing* originated in the early 1990s as a metaphor for making computer power as easy to access as an electric power grid.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The power grid metaphor for accessible computing quickly became canonical when Ian Foster and Carl Kesselman published their seminal work, "The Grid: Blueprint for a new computing infrastructure" (1999).
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] This was preceded by decades by the metaphor of utility computing (1961): computing as a public utility, analogous to the phone system.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] CPU scavenging and volunteer computing were popularized beginning in 1997 by distributed.net and later in 1999 by SETI@home to harness the power of networked PCs worldwide, in order to solve CPU-intensive research problems.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The ideas of the grid (including those from distributed computing, object-oriented programming, and Web services) were brought together by Ian Foster and Steve Tuecke of the University of Chicago, and Carl Kesselman of the University of Southern California's Information Sciences Institute.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The trio, who led the effort to create the Globus Toolkit, is widely regarded as the "fathers of the grid".
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] While the Globus Toolkit remains the de facto standard for building grid solutions, a number of other tools have been built that answer some subset of services needed to create an enterprise or global grid.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] In 2007 the term cloud computing came into popularity, which is conceptually similar to the canonical Foster definition of grid computing (in terms of computing resources being consumed as electricity is from the power grid) and earlier utility computing.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] In November 2006, Edward Seidel received the Sidney Fernbach Award at the Supercomputing Conference in Tampa, Florida.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Also, as of March 2019, the Bitcoin Network had a measured computing power equivalent to over 80,000 exaFLOPS (Floating-point Operations Per Second).
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Grid computing offers a way to solve Grand Challenge problems such as protein folding, financial modeling, earthquake simulation, and climate/weather modeling, and was integral in enabling the Large Hadron Collider at CERN.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Grids offer a way of using information technology resources optimally inside an organization.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] They also provide a means for offering information technology as a utility for commercial and noncommercial clients, with those clients paying only for what they use, as with electricity or water.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] As of October 2016, over 4 million machines running the open-source Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC) platform are members of the World Community Grid.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] One of the projects using BOINC is SETI@home, which was using more than 400,000 computers to achieve 0.828 TFLOPS as of October 2016.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] As of October 2016 Folding@home, which is not part of BOINC, achieved more than 101 x86-equivalent petaflops on over 110,000 machines.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The European Union funded projects through the framework programmes of the European Commission.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] BEinGRID (Business Experiments in Grid) was a research project funded by the European Commission as an Integrated Project under the Sixth Framework Programme (FP6) sponsorship program.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Started on June 1, 2006, the project ran 42 months, until November 2009.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The project was coordinated by Atos Origin.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] According to the project fact sheet, their mission is “to establish effective routes to foster the adoption of grid computing across the EU and to stimulate research into innovative business models using Grid technologies”.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] To extract best practice and common themes from the experimental implementations, two groups of consultants are analyzing a series of pilots, one technical, one business.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The project is significant not only for its long duration but also for its budget, which at 24.8 million Euros, is the largest of any FP6 integrated project.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Of this, 15.7 million is provided by the European Commission and the remainder by its 98 contributing partner companies.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Since the end of the project, the results of BEinGRID have been taken up and carried forward by IT-Tude.com.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The Enabling Grids for E-sciencE project, based in the European Union and included sites in Asia and the United States, was a follow-up project to the European DataGrid (EDG) and evolved into the European Grid Infrastructure.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] This, along with the Worldwide LHC Computing Grid (WLCG), was developed to support experiments using the CERN Large Hadron Collider.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] A list of active sites participating within WLCG can be found online as can real time monitoring of the EGEE infrastructure.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The relevant software and documentation is also publicly accessible.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] There is speculation that dedicated fiber optic links, such as those installed by CERN to address the WLCG's data-intensive needs, may one day be available to home users thereby providing internet services at speeds up to 10,000 times faster than a traditional broadband connection.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The European Grid Infrastructure has been also used for other research activities and experiments such as the simulation of oncological clinical trials.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The distributed.net project was started in 1997.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The NASA Advanced Supercomputing facility (NAS) ran genetic algorithms using the Condor cycle scavenger running on about 350 Sun Microsystems and SGI workstations.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] In 2001, United Devices operated the United Devices Cancer Research Project based on its Grid MP product, which cycle-scavenges on volunteer PCs connected to the Internet.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] The project ran on about 3.1 million machines before its close in 2007.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] Recent innovations have explored the integration of blockchain technology with grid computing principles.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] For example, the VirtEngine system, detailed in granted Australian patent AU2024203136, proposes a decentralized model that combines a distributed computing network with a Proof-of-Stake blockchain-based framework for identification, authentication, and resource management.
[src:aws-batch/grid-computing] This approach aims to create an autonomous system for managing a decentralized cloud marketplace and a distributed supercomputer, utilizing consumer & provider based computing resources to power a globally distributed grid computing network.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] HPC integrates systems administration (including network and security knowledge), parallel computing and distributed computing into a multidisciplinary field that combines digital electronics, computer architecture, system software, programming languages, algorithms and computational techniques.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] HPC technologies are the tools and systems used to implement and create high performance computing systems.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] Since around 2005, HPC systems have shifted from supercomputing to computing clusters and grids.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] Because of the need of networking in clusters and grids, High Performance Computing Technologies are achieved by the use of a collapsed network backbone, because the collapsed backbone architecture is simple to troubleshoot and upgrades can be applied to a single router as opposed to multiple ones.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] HPC integrates with data analytics in AI engineering workflows to generate new data streams that increase a simulation's ability to answer the "what if" questions.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] The term is most commonly associated with computing used for scientific research or computational science.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] A related term, high-performance technical computing (HPTC), generally refers to the engineering applications of cluster-based computing (such as computational fluid dynamics and the building and testing of virtual prototypes).
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] HPC has also been applied to business uses such as data warehouses, line of business (LOB) applications, and transaction processing.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] High-performance computing (HPC) as a term arose after the term "supercomputing".
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] HPC is sometimes used as a synonym for supercomputing; but, in other contexts, "supercomputer" is used to refer to a more powerful subset of "high-performance computers", and the term "supercomputing" becomes a subset of "high-performance computing".
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] The potential for confusion over the use of these terms is apparent.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] Because most current applications are not designed for HPC technologies but are retrofitted, they are not designed or tested for scaling to more powerful processors or machines.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] Since networking clusters and grids use multiple processors and computers, these scaling problems can cripple critical systems in future supercomputing systems.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] Therefore, either the existing tools do not address the needs of the high performance computing community or the HPC community is unaware of these tools.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] In government and research institutions, scientists simulate galaxy formation and evolution, fusion energy, and global warming, as well as work to create more accurate short- and long-term weather forecasts.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] The world's tenth most powerful supercomputer in 2008, IBM Roadrunner (located at the United States Department of Energy's Los Alamos National Laboratory) simulated the performance, safety, and reliability of nuclear weapons and certifies their functionality.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] TOP500 ranks the world's 500 fastest high-performance computers, as measured by the High Performance LINPACK (HPL) benchmark.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] Not all existing computers are ranked, either because they are ineligible (e.g., they cannot run the HPL benchmark) or because their owners have not submitted an HPL score (e.g., because they do not wish the size of their system to become public information, for defense reasons).
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] In addition, the use of the single LINPACK benchmark is controversial, in that no single measure can test all aspects of a high-performance computer.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] To help overcome the limitations of the LINPACK test, the U.S. government commissioned one of its originators, Jack Dongarra of the University of Tennessee, to create a suite of benchmark tests that includes LINPACK and others, called the HPC Challenge benchmark suite.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] This evolving suite has been used in some HPC procurements, but, because it is not reducible to a single number, it has been unable to overcome the publicity advantage of the less useful TOP500 LINPACK test.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] The TOP500 list is updated twice a year, once in June at the ISC European Supercomputing Conference and again at a US Supercomputing Conference in November.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] Many ideas for the new wave of grid computing were originally borrowed from HPC.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] Traditionally, HPC has involved an on-premises infrastructure, investing in supercomputers or computer clusters.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] Over the last decade, cloud computing has grown in popularity for offering computer resources in the commercial sector regardless of their investment capabilities.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] Some characteristics like scalability and containerization also have raised interest in academia.
[src:aws-batch/high-performance-computing] However security in the cloud concerns such as data confidentiality are still considered when deciding between cloud or on-premise HPC resources.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] A **job scheduler** is a computer application for controlling unattended background program execution of jobs.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] This is commonly called **batch scheduling**, as execution of non-interactive jobs is often called batch processing, though traditional *job* and *batch* are distinguished and contrasted; see that page for details.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] Other synonyms include **batch system**, **distributed resource management system** (**DRMS**), **distributed resource manager** (**DRM**), and, commonly today, **workload automation** (**WLA**).
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] The data structure of jobs to run is known as the job queue.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] Modern job schedulers typically provide a graphical user interface and a single point of control for definition and monitoring of background executions in a distributed network of computers.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] Increasingly, job schedulers are required to orchestrate the integration of real-time business activities with traditional background IT processing across different operating system platforms and business application environments.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] If software from a completely different area includes all or some of those features, this software can be considered to have job scheduling capabilities.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] Most operating systems, such as Unix and Windows, provide basic job scheduling capabilities, notably by at and batch, cron, and the Windows Task Scheduler.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] Web hosting services provide job scheduling capabilities through a control panel or a webcron solution.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] Many programs such as DBMS, backup, ERPs, and BPM also include relevant job-scheduling capabilities.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] Operating system ("OS") or point program supplied job-scheduling will not usually provide the ability to schedule beyond a single OS instance or outside the remit of the specific program.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] These advanced capabilities can be written by in-house developers but are more often provided by suppliers who specialize in systems-management software.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] There are many concepts that are central to almost every job scheduler implementation and that are widely recognized with minimal variations: jobs, dependencies, job streams, and users.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] Beyond the basic, single OS instance scheduling tools there are two major architectures that exist for Job Scheduling software.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] Job schedulers have been one of the major components of IT infrastructure since the early mainframe systems.
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] At first, stacks of punched cards were processed one after the other, hence the term "batch processing".
[src:aws-batch/job-scheduler] Various schemes are used to decide which particular job to run.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:aws-batch/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] In computing, a **task** is a unit of execution or a unit of work.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] The term is ambiguous; precise alternative terms include *process*, light-weight process, *thread* (for execution), *step*, *request*, or *query* (for work).
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] In the adjacent diagram, there are queues of incoming work to do and outgoing completed work, and a thread pool of threads to perform this work.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] Either the work units themselves or the threads that perform the work can be referred to as "tasks", and these can be referred to respectively as requests/responses/threads, incoming tasks/completed tasks/threads (as illustrated), or requests/responses/tasks.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] In the sense of "unit of execution", in some operating systems, a task is synonymous with a process, and in others with a thread.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] In non-interactive execution (batch processing), a task is a unit of execution within a job, with the task itself typically a process.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] The term "multitasking" primarily refers to the processing sense – multiple tasks *executing* at the same time – but has nuances of the work sense of multiple tasks being *performed* at the same time.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] In online systems, tasks most commonly correspond to a single *request* (in request–response architectures) or a *query* (in information retrieval), either a single stage of handling, or the whole system-wide handling.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] The term task in OS/360 through z/OS is roughly equivalent to light-weight process; the tasks in a job step share an address space.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] However, in MVS/ESA through z/OS, a task or Service Request Block (SRB) may have access to other address spaces via its access list.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] The term *task* is used in the Linux kernel (at least since v2.6.13, up to and including v4.8) to refer to a unit of execution, which may share various system resources with other tasks on the system.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] Depending on the level of sharing, the task may be regarded as a conventional thread or process.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] Tasks are brought into existence using the `clone()` system call, where a user can specify the desired level of resource sharing.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] The term was popularized with the introduction of OS/360 (announced 1964), which featured Multiprogramming with a Fixed number of Tasks (MFT) and Multiprogramming with a Variable number of Tasks (MVT).
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] In this case tasks were identified with light-weight processes, a job consisted of a number of tasks, and, later, tasks could have sub-tasks (in modern terminology, child processes).
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] Today the term "task" is used very ambiguously.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] For example, the Windows Task Manager manages (running) *processes*, while Windows Task Scheduler schedules *programs* to execute in future, what is traditionally known as a job scheduler, and uses the `.job` extension.
[src:aws-batch/task-computing] By contrast, the term "task queue" is commonly used in the sense of "units of work".
